WEBVTT

00:02.335 --> 00:05.213
{\an8}<i>NEWSWOMAN: We end our broadcast</i>
<i>tonight with some sad news.</i>

00:05.296 --> 00:07.966
{\an8}<i>Beloved mayor Trina Grant</i>
<i>has died in a car accident,</i>

00:08.048 --> 00:10.760
{\an8}<i>leaving the small town</i>
<i>of Littleton in mourning.</i>

00:10.844 --> 00:13.513
{\an8}<i>Grant was credited with raising</i>
<i>the profile of their community</i>

00:13.596 --> 00:15.598
{\an8}<i>and making it a quaint</i>
<i>and bustling tourist stop</i>

00:15.682 --> 00:16.808
{\an8}<i>along the highway.</i>

00:16.891 --> 00:20.103
{\an8}<i>Recently, she had spearheaded</i>
<i>a key city council vote</i>

00:20.186 --> 00:22.439
{\an8}<i>that fended off the extension</i>
<i>of Interstate 10,</i>

00:22.522 --> 00:25.108
{\an8}<i>which would have cut Littleton</i>
<i>off from traffic altogether.</i>

00:25.191 --> 00:28.278
{\an8}<i>She is succeeded in office</i>
<i>by town treasurer John Conley,</i>

00:28.361 --> 00:31.239
{\an8}<i>who has been a longtime</i>
<i>advocate for the interstate.</i>

00:31.322 --> 00:33.116
{\an8}<i>Grant's passing</i>
<i>will likely allow construction</i>

00:33.199 --> 00:34.993
{\an8}<i>on the project to proceed.</i>

00:35.076 --> 00:37.620
{\an8}<i>The economic results of that</i>
<i>are yet to be seen.</i>

00:37.704 --> 00:40.165
{\an8}<i>Mayor Grant is survived</i>
<i>by her husband Jason.</i>

00:40.248 --> 00:41.833
{\an8}<i>Our thoughts tonight are</i>
<i>with her family,</i>

00:41.916 --> 00:44.377
{\an8}<i>friends and community.</i>

00:48.882 --> 00:51.092
♪ ♪

01:00.101 --> 01:02.812
(crow cawing in distance)

01:16.951 --> 01:18.328
(car door closes)

01:18.411 --> 01:20.413
(car door opens)

01:29.923 --> 01:32.133
Morning, Mr. Mayor.

01:45.438 --> 01:47.440
(door closes)

02:07.627 --> 02:09.878
-(knocking)
-JASON: Come in.

02:11.464 --> 02:13.091
(door opens)

02:13.174 --> 02:15.343
Hi, Mr. Grant.
How's it going?

02:15.426 --> 02:18.054
I told you to call me Jason,
Emilio.

02:18.137 --> 02:19.514
Uh, Mr. Grant was
my father's name.

02:19.597 --> 02:21.432
And I'm fine. Thanks.

02:21.516 --> 02:23.726
Right. Jason.

02:23.810 --> 02:25.979
I brought the candle and cupcake

02:26.062 --> 02:27.605
-you asked for.
-Oh.

02:29.315 --> 02:30.859
Little tip.

02:30.942 --> 02:32.902
Thank you.

02:32.986 --> 02:34.404
So, what you been working on?

02:34.487 --> 02:38.575
You know,
just a couple... sketches.

02:38.658 --> 02:40.159
Couple sketches?

02:40.243 --> 02:42.453
Wow.

02:42.537 --> 02:44.080
Dude.

02:44.873 --> 02:47.584
Damn.

02:47.667 --> 02:49.210
These colors are crazy, man.

02:49.294 --> 02:50.879
(laughs)

02:50.962 --> 02:53.006
Is that the mayor?

02:53.673 --> 02:55.091
Wow.

02:55.174 --> 02:56.968
This is my favorite.

02:57.051 --> 02:58.261
-(chuckles)
-Man, you really nailed

02:58.344 --> 03:00.847
that stupid look
he always has on his face.

03:00.930 --> 03:01.890
These are...

03:01.973 --> 03:04.559
Wow, man,
you're talented as hell.

03:05.351 --> 03:08.771
Why do you stay
in this room, man?

03:08.855 --> 03:11.232
-It's kind of depressing.
-Um...

03:11.316 --> 03:16.112
you know, my wife and I
had that house down on Elm.

03:18.323 --> 03:20.783
It didn't feel right
staying there without her.

03:20.867 --> 03:24.287
Pastor Nicki let me stay up here
as long as I'm useful.

03:24.370 --> 03:27.332
Plus, up here, she said
I might feel closer to God.

03:29.876 --> 03:30.919
They're so good.

03:31.002 --> 03:34.631
Yeah, tell your mom
I'll drop by the diner later.

03:34.714 --> 03:36.257
So...

03:38.468 --> 03:40.011
...do you?

03:40.845 --> 03:42.972
Do I what?

03:43.056 --> 03:46.643
Feel closer to God?

03:58.738 --> 04:00.990
NICKI:
Hey, Jason.

04:03.451 --> 04:04.160
(gasps softly)

04:04.243 --> 04:07.163
-Oh, Jason.
-(scissors snipping)

04:07.246 --> 04:09.832
Jason,
the flowers look beautiful.

04:09.916 --> 04:13.336
I see you're, uh,
rocking some new nail polish.

04:13.419 --> 04:16.005
That peach color's
looking really good.

04:16.089 --> 04:19.132
(chuckles)
Thank you.

04:19.216 --> 04:21.678
Hey, Pastor, I was wondering...

04:21.761 --> 04:23.513
do you think I could clear out

04:23.596 --> 04:25.640
some of the other junk
in the attic?

04:25.723 --> 04:28.685
Free up that side window,
let in more light?

04:28.768 --> 04:30.520
That junk predates me.

04:30.603 --> 04:32.563
But if you're in the mood
to get it out, go for it.

04:32.647 --> 04:35.066
You'll be doing the church
a favor.

04:37.235 --> 04:40.321
Hard day today, huh?

04:40.405 --> 04:42.073
Yeah.

04:42.156 --> 04:45.076
I miss her, too.
We all do.

04:45.159 --> 04:48.371
Trina never would have let
the town get like this.

04:48.454 --> 04:50.540
She actually gave a damn.

04:50.623 --> 04:52.917
She was a good person.

04:53.001 --> 04:54.419
A good friend,

04:54.502 --> 04:55.878
a great mayor.

04:55.962 --> 04:59.632
And what happened
isn't on you, J.

04:59.716 --> 05:03.720
We need to move forward.

05:10.476 --> 05:12.228
Move forward?

05:12.311 --> 05:14.731
Well, first I'm gonna move you.

05:15.982 --> 05:19.068
♪ ♪

05:40.840 --> 05:44.802
What... is this?

05:45.803 --> 05:48.598
Where did you come from?

05:48.681 --> 05:50.767
♪ ♪

05:57.857 --> 06:00.276
Nice details.

06:01.235 --> 06:04.113
These details are perfect.

06:07.867 --> 06:12.538
No... freaking way.

06:13.164 --> 06:16.459
Looks just like the place.

06:20.880 --> 06:23.132
Wow.

06:23.800 --> 06:26.135
Got the cracks in the ground.

06:26.219 --> 06:28.638
What the heck?

06:30.056 --> 06:32.266
Hmm, wonder what this does.

06:32.350 --> 06:34.769
(squeaking, clacking)

06:35.770 --> 06:37.230
(click)

06:37.313 --> 06:38.147
(whirring)

06:38.231 --> 06:40.983
(clacking)

06:41.067 --> 06:43.152
(overlapping mechanical sounds)

06:49.909 --> 06:52.703
(chuckles):
No way.

06:52.787 --> 06:53.955
What?

06:54.038 --> 06:55.414
(laughs)

06:55.498 --> 06:59.043
Oh, man, that looks, that looks
exactly like the diner.

06:59.127 --> 07:01.504
Geez, Louise.

07:02.797 --> 07:05.258
(whispers):
Wow.

07:09.095 --> 07:10.972
This is crazy.

07:11.055 --> 07:13.182
Wait.

07:13.933 --> 07:16.394
Wait, is that...?

07:20.731 --> 07:24.569
No, there's no,
there's no way that's me.

07:29.866 --> 07:30.741
{\an8}(spritzes)

07:30.825 --> 07:33.953
{\an8}(rain falls)

07:35.955 --> 07:38.374
No.

07:40.501 --> 07:41.210
No.

07:41.294 --> 07:42.837
What the...

07:42.920 --> 07:45.923
hell was that about?

07:54.265 --> 07:55.808
Jesus.

08:21.000 --> 08:23.336
NARRATOR:
Mr. Jason Grant.

08:24.420 --> 08:30.176
A man looking to make a big
difference in a small town.

08:30.259 --> 08:33.596
But being the change
you wish to see in the world

08:33.679 --> 08:34.931
is a lot more complicated

08:35.014 --> 08:39.227
when you've got that whole world
in your hands.

08:40.352 --> 08:42.897
It's all a matter
of perspective

08:42.980 --> 08:47.777
here in The Twilight Zone.

08:47.860 --> 08:48.986
<i>(The Twilight Zone</i> theme
playing)

08:49.070 --> 08:50.154
<i>NARRATOR: You're traveling</i>
<i>through another dimension,</i>

08:50.238 --> 08:54.408
<i>a dimension not only of</i>
<i>sight and sound but of mind.</i>

08:54.492 --> 08:57.620
<i>It is the middle ground</i>
<i>between light and shadow,</i>

08:57.703 --> 09:00.414
<i>between science</i>
<i>and superstition.</i>

09:00.498 --> 09:03.084
{\an8}<i>And it lies between</i>
<i>the pit of one's fears</i>

09:03.167 --> 09:05.753
{\an8}<i>and the summit</i>
<i>of one's knowledge.</i>

09:05.836 --> 09:09.131
<i>You are now traveling through</i>
<i>a dimension of imagination.</i>

09:09.215 --> 09:13.261
<i>You've just crossed over</i>
<i>into The Twilight Zone.</i>

09:18.391 --> 09:20.393
{\an8}♪ ♪

09:32.363 --> 09:34.448
{\an8}<i>BEAU: I'm telling you,</i>
<i>that rain was weird.</i>

09:34.532 --> 09:36.784
{\an8}Only lasted a few seconds,
and then...

09:36.867 --> 09:38.369
{\an8}(clicks tongue)
not another drop.

09:38.452 --> 09:39.620
{\an8}That's some crazy weather
for Littleton.

09:39.704 --> 09:40.454
{\an8}(stammers)
Biblical.

09:40.538 --> 09:41.539
{\an8}Yeah, I heard
it only hit a block

09:41.622 --> 09:43.833
{\an8}on Main Street, too.
I didn't get a drop at my place.

09:43.916 --> 09:45.126
{\an8}ANA:
I almost didn't recognize you.

09:45.918 --> 09:47.336
{\an8}Can I get you some coffee?

09:47.420 --> 09:48.254
{\an8}-Sure. Yeah.
-Yeah.

09:48.337 --> 09:50.798
{\an8}So, what,
the rain got you out of hiding?

09:50.881 --> 09:52.508
{\an8}Yeah, that was, uh...

09:52.591 --> 09:54.969
{\an8}really something.

09:55.052 --> 09:57.680
{\an8}Slow day today, huh?

09:57.763 --> 10:00.558
{\an8}That interstate really dried up
everything for everyone,

10:00.641 --> 10:01.767
{\an8}except the mayor.

10:01.851 --> 10:04.979
{\an8}Too bad I didn't know about that
before I signed the lease.

10:05.062 --> 10:06.188
{\an8}Can I get you started
with anything?

10:06.272 --> 10:07.815
{\an8}Just the caffeine.

10:07.898 --> 10:10.318
{\an8}All right.
Well... coffee's on me.

10:10.401 --> 10:12.028
{\an8}-Thanks.
-FARMER: You know,
that whole storm,

10:12.111 --> 10:13.529
{\an8}it barely missed my place.

10:13.612 --> 10:14.822
{\an8}Shame, too.

10:14.905 --> 10:17.366
{\an8}I could've used
the free car wash.

10:17.450 --> 10:19.076
{\an8}Well, it'd take an act of God
to clean that hunk of junk.

10:19.160 --> 10:20.703
{\an8}-(laughs)
-Shut up.

10:20.786 --> 10:22.038
{\an8}ANA:
All right.

10:22.121 --> 10:23.039
{\an8}You good?

10:23.122 --> 10:24.081
{\an8}-Eh.
-Perfect.

10:24.165 --> 10:25.124
{\an8}Oh, remember, next week,

10:25.207 --> 10:27.335
{\an8}we're gonna start
on painting the wall, okay?

10:27.418 --> 10:29.045
{\an8}No excuses.
Rain or shine.

10:29.128 --> 10:30.713
{\an8}EMILIO:
Right, Mom. Fresh paint?

10:30.796 --> 10:32.715
{\an8}Yeah, that'll turn everything
around here.

10:32.798 --> 10:35.217
{\an8}ANA: Hey. Paint works wonders.
You'll see.

10:35.301 --> 10:37.553
{\an8}Come on. Get your stuff ready.

10:37.636 --> 10:38.554
{\an8}You guys good?

10:38.637 --> 10:40.014
{\an8}MAN: Can I get some syrup,
if you don't mind?

10:40.097 --> 10:42.892
{\an8}-ANA: Yes.
-Thank you.

10:42.975 --> 10:45.686
{\an8}♪ ♪

10:47.688 --> 10:50.024
{\an8}Nice details.

11:06.999 --> 11:08.751
{\an8}ANA:
Emilito?

11:08.834 --> 11:10.419
{\an8}Huh?

11:10.503 --> 11:11.712
{\an8}(Ana scoffs)

11:11.796 --> 11:13.589
{\an8}Did you do this?

11:13.673 --> 11:15.257
{\an8}When?

11:15.341 --> 11:17.593
{\an8}I mean, why didn't you use
the paint that was in the shed?

11:17.676 --> 11:19.136
{\an8}Mom, this wasn't me.

11:19.220 --> 11:21.389
{\an8}Well, then who was it?

11:21.472 --> 11:23.724
{\an8}-JASON: Wow.
-(Ana scoffs)

11:23.808 --> 11:25.768
{\an8}Did you see this paint job?

11:25.851 --> 11:27.937
{\an8}Oh, yeah.
Looks amazing.

11:28.020 --> 11:29.814
{\an8}Yeah, well, whoever did it
did it without my permission.

11:29.897 --> 11:31.732
{\an8}I mean, you know the mayor
still owns this building.

11:31.816 --> 11:35.111
{\an8}He's not a "let's paint
the walls orange" kind of guy.

11:35.194 --> 11:36.278
{\an8}Looks pretty incredible,
if you ask me.

11:36.362 --> 11:39.615
{\an8}I think whoever did it
really brightened this place up.

11:40.699 --> 11:42.284
{\an8}I mean, it's a bit strange.

11:42.368 --> 11:44.120
{\an8}Bright orange
is definitely a choice.

11:44.203 --> 11:46.789
{\an8}I think it's more peach.

11:48.332 --> 11:50.126
{\an8}You know, maybe you're right.

11:50.209 --> 11:52.461
{\an8}It kind of does
cheer things up a bit.

11:52.545 --> 11:55.631
{\an8}Yeah? Well, then who cares
what Conley thinks?

11:55.714 --> 11:57.675
{\an8}-Yeah.
-Yeah.

12:20.573 --> 12:22.616
{\an8}This...

12:24.410 --> 12:26.287
{\an8}(mutters):
Piece of crap.

12:27.371 --> 12:31.125
{\an8}-MR. TURNER: Watch your step.
-(Mrs. Turner shouts)

12:31.208 --> 12:32.168
{\an8}-Oh, my God.
-Mrs. Turner?

12:32.251 --> 12:33.961
{\an8}Honey, are you okay?

12:34.044 --> 12:36.630
{\an8}-You okay?
-Uh, uh, I'm fine.

12:36.714 --> 12:41.635
{\an8}I'm, I-I-I'm fine, I... I keep
forgetting where that hole is.

12:41.719 --> 12:43.554
{\an8}Damn near broke my hip.

12:43.637 --> 12:47.057
{\an8}-Someone should fix that.
-Yeah, right.

12:47.141 --> 12:49.393
{\an8}No, we put a note
in that suggestion box,

12:49.477 --> 12:51.228
{\an8}but he doesn't even bother
to look.

12:51.312 --> 12:53.314
{\an8}And Lord knows the last time
the mayor even glanced

12:53.397 --> 12:54.857
{\an8}at the thing.

12:54.940 --> 12:57.151
{\an8}♪ ♪

