{\an8}♪<i> He's got the whole world</i>
<i>in his hands...</i> ♪

14:15.521 --> 14:17.439
{\an5}FARMER:
So they just decided
not to move?

14:17.523 --> 14:19.108
I'm glad they're staying,
but it's kind of weird.

14:19.191 --> 14:20.943
All these fixes around town
must have changed their mind.

14:21.026 --> 14:22.278
I mean, you got to admit,

14:22.361 --> 14:23.612
it's looking a lot better
around here.

14:23.696 --> 14:25.614
Yeah, even Mrs. Turner's pothole
got fixed.

14:25.698 --> 14:28.492
You know, I've been talking
about that pothole for ages.

14:28.576 --> 14:30.160
I'm glad someone was listening.

14:30.244 --> 14:33.831
♪<i> He's got the whole world</i>
<i>in His hands.</i> ♪

14:33.914 --> 14:37.751
{\an5}EMILIO:
Mayor Conley, I don't know
who painted the diner.

14:39.670 --> 14:41.630
You know what happens
to smart-asses?

14:41.714 --> 14:43.591
-They get to be mayor?
-Emilio.

14:43.674 --> 14:46.135
I am so sorry.
It won't happen again.

14:46.218 --> 14:48.762
{\an5}CONLEY:
Well, next time,
it's coming out of your rent.

14:50.723 --> 14:53.309
(sighs)

14:53.392 --> 14:55.769
-You okay, Mr. Mayor?
-I'm f-fine.

14:55.853 --> 14:58.606
Thank you for your concern,
Mister, uh...?

14:58.689 --> 15:00.274
-Grant.
-Right, Grant. Yes, of course.

15:00.357 --> 15:01.859
-Jason Grant.
-Right.

15:01.942 --> 15:04.612
You actually used to work
with my wife.

15:05.904 --> 15:06.822
Trina.

15:06.905 --> 15:09.158
Oh. (exclaims) Right.

15:09.241 --> 15:11.785
I'm so sorry for your loss.

15:22.880 --> 15:24.465
I've been fighting
with the mayor's office

15:24.548 --> 15:26.383
for months
to get that tree removed.

15:26.467 --> 15:28.969
They said it was too expensive.

15:29.053 --> 15:30.971
But it's gone now.

15:31.055 --> 15:32.681
Trunk, stump, roots.

15:32.765 --> 15:35.017
(chuckles):
Poof. Gone.

15:35.100 --> 15:37.019
Well, who the hell did that?

15:37.102 --> 15:38.520
MAN:
Whoever did it,

15:38.604 --> 15:41.148
-I owe 'em a beer.
-(chuckles)

15:41.231 --> 15:43.525
(exhales)
Maybe things are, uh,

15:43.609 --> 15:45.027
getting better here.

15:45.110 --> 15:47.696
{\an8}-Think I just might
stick around.
-Yeah. Uh,

15:47.780 --> 15:50.532
{\an8}looks like things
are turning around.

15:50.616 --> 15:53.160
{\an8}Reminds me of when Littleton
used to be something.

15:53.243 --> 15:55.204
Feels like wrongs are
finally being righted, you know?

15:55.287 --> 15:58.040
It's like a guardian angel's
come to town or something.

15:58.123 --> 16:00.542
It's Mayor Conley.

16:01.794 --> 16:03.671
-What?
-MAN: He should be trying

16:03.754 --> 16:04.880
to get in our good graces.

16:04.963 --> 16:06.340
He's got that reelection
next year.

16:06.423 --> 16:08.384
Election.

16:08.467 --> 16:10.511
Not reelection.

16:10.594 --> 16:12.012
-Sorry?
-Mayor Grant,

16:12.096 --> 16:14.682
she passed away
in the middle of her term.

16:14.765 --> 16:16.725
The order of succession
just fell into his lap.

16:16.809 --> 16:19.061
He was never actually elected.

16:19.144 --> 16:20.562
Ever.

16:20.646 --> 16:22.856
MAN: I could care less
why he's doing it.

16:22.940 --> 16:24.400
Yesterday
I had a thousand-dollar problem

16:24.483 --> 16:27.111
in my backyard,
and today I don't.

16:27.194 --> 16:29.571
ESTHER: Well, whatever
you call it, maybe he <i> is</i> trying

16:29.655 --> 16:32.574
to butter up this town
for votes.

16:32.658 --> 16:35.077
Here's to the good and handy
Mayor Conley.

16:35.160 --> 16:36.245
Huh?

16:36.328 --> 16:37.871
I'm good.

16:46.422 --> 16:48.757
(sighs)

16:48.841 --> 16:50.300
What would you do, Trina?

16:50.384 --> 16:52.761
The town is feeling
a bit more like it did

16:52.845 --> 16:54.972
when you were around,
but the mayor's highway

16:55.055 --> 16:56.724
is pushing everyone going
in this direction

16:56.807 --> 16:58.642
right by Littleton completely.

16:58.726 --> 17:01.311
Like they don't even know
we exist.

17:01.395 --> 17:03.647
♪ ♪

17:24.001 --> 17:25.335
MAN:
It's so big,

17:25.419 --> 17:27.755
people are seeing the sign
from the highway.

17:27.838 --> 17:29.757
Got to get new pumps.

17:29.840 --> 17:32.259
I've never seen
so many people before.

17:32.342 --> 17:34.261
This is crazy.

17:34.344 --> 17:36.305
♪ ♪

17:36.388 --> 17:38.932
(indistinct chatter)

17:39.975 --> 17:42.352
JASON:
Let there be light.

17:42.436 --> 17:44.772
(electrical buzzing)

17:53.906 --> 17:55.908
(church bell ringing)

18:00.704 --> 18:02.122
(organ music playing)

18:02.206 --> 18:03.832
How's the grandbaby?
I love that.

18:03.916 --> 18:07.461
{\an8}Hello, you newlyweds.
(chuckles)

18:07.544 --> 18:10.839
{\an8}Good for you.
Good for you. Good for you.

18:10.923 --> 18:12.674
{\an8}Hello. Hello.

18:12.758 --> 18:14.134
(quiet chatter)

18:14.218 --> 18:16.720
Hi, folks.
(chuckles)

18:16.804 --> 18:18.680
(chatter continues)

18:18.764 --> 18:21.975
-Great to see you.
-You came.

18:22.059 --> 18:25.521
-Hi. Oh, I love your-your vest.
-Good to see you.

18:25.604 --> 18:27.356
Everybody thinks
he's The Helper.

18:27.439 --> 18:29.149
Yeah, bet he loves it.

18:29.233 --> 18:32.110
He coin that nickname himself?

18:32.194 --> 18:34.905
-Holy hell.
-(whispers): Really? At church?

18:34.988 --> 18:38.325
{\an5}-Glo, they're smiling
real smiles.
-(clears throat)

18:38.408 --> 18:40.661
Maybe they're
finally warming up to me.

18:40.744 --> 18:42.913
Well, well, well.

18:42.996 --> 18:45.666
Haven't seen some of y'all
in a minute.

18:45.749 --> 18:48.669
Still glad we got enough people
in this town to fill these pews.

18:48.752 --> 18:52.172
I was starting to feel like
a shepherd without a flock.

18:52.256 --> 18:54.258
-(congregation laughs)
-I, um...

18:54.341 --> 18:57.511
I know that our community
has been evaporating

18:57.594 --> 19:02.057
due to certain
infrastructure developments.

19:02.140 --> 19:05.310
But today,
today we are brought together

19:05.394 --> 19:07.354
by something different.

19:07.437 --> 19:10.941
We are brought together
by a special set of miracles

19:11.024 --> 19:13.068
that have caused a rebirth
in Littleton.

19:13.151 --> 19:15.946
Gifts from someone
who my husband,

19:16.029 --> 19:18.824
Francisco, calls <i> El Ayudante.</i>

19:19.825 --> 19:22.119
The Helper.

19:22.202 --> 19:25.163
-BEAU: We know it's Conley.
-(congregation chuckles)

19:26.999 --> 19:29.710
NICKI: Well, I know
some of you have some, uh,

19:29.793 --> 19:31.378
pretty wild theories
on who it is.

19:31.461 --> 19:32.921
-It isn't you, right?
-And I know, 'cause I've heard

19:33.005 --> 19:34.923
some pretty outrageous ones.
But whoever it is,

19:35.007 --> 19:36.925
someone in our community cares.

19:37.009 --> 19:38.093
<i>El Ayudante</i>

19:38.176 --> 19:40.137
is taking responsibility
for his neighbors.

19:40.220 --> 19:41.763
For his friends.

19:41.847 --> 19:43.390
Fixing our street.

19:43.473 --> 19:45.392
Painting our diner.

19:45.475 --> 19:46.935
Hauling our trash.

19:47.019 --> 19:48.937
Making our town

19:49.021 --> 19:51.481
-successful again.
-CONGREGATION: Amen.

19:52.983 --> 19:55.277
BEAU:
Thank you, Mayor Conley.

19:55.360 --> 19:57.404
(indistinct chatter)

20:04.328 --> 20:05.495
<i>(applause)</i>

20:05.579 --> 20:07.831
(whooping)

20:09.541 --> 20:11.877
(cheering and whistling)

20:14.004 --> 20:16.006
<i>El Ayudante.</i>

20:20.010 --> 20:22.346
Thank you, Mayor Conley.
You've got my vote.

20:23.513 --> 20:25.515
♪ ♪

20:51.541 --> 20:53.543
♪ ♪

20:58.298 --> 21:01.134
<i>-(thud)</i>
<i>-(car alarm blaring)</i>

21:02.928 --> 21:04.680
CONLEY:
You've got to be kidding me!

21:04.763 --> 21:07.641
WOMAN:
What happened?

21:07.724 --> 21:09.393
Why?!

21:09.476 --> 21:11.645
I can't believe this.
Who did this?

21:11.728 --> 21:13.480
TURNER:
What are the odds?

21:13.563 --> 21:14.982
You're right square.

21:15.065 --> 21:17.442
Thank God no one got hurt.

21:20.654 --> 21:22.572
Did anyone see anything?

21:22.656 --> 21:23.824
Huh?

21:23.907 --> 21:25.367
(Emilio chuckling)

21:26.660 --> 21:27.911
What about you?

21:30.622 --> 21:33.000
-Is this funny to you?
-Hey! What's going on?

21:33.083 --> 21:35.043
Your boy here
is having a big laugh.

21:35.127 --> 21:38.547
Oh, you got a real troublemaker
on your hands here.

21:38.630 --> 21:40.173
My son is not a troublemaker.

21:40.257 --> 21:42.009
And why are you targeting him,
anyways?

21:42.092 --> 21:42.884
If you're gonna stand here

21:42.968 --> 21:45.053
in front of everyone
and assign blame,

21:45.137 --> 21:46.513
then you better back that up
with proof.

21:46.596 --> 21:49.474
-Yeah!
-Let's go, Emilio.<i> Vamos.</i>

21:49.558 --> 21:51.560
♪ ♪

21:59.818 --> 22:01.695
Of course!
(laughs)

22:01.778 --> 22:03.071
It's not his-his fault.

22:03.155 --> 22:05.866
He's just a kid.
And-and this

22:05.949 --> 22:08.410
is just a-a thing.

22:08.493 --> 22:10.203
It's just a car.

22:10.287 --> 22:12.748
Because we don't dwell

22:12.831 --> 22:15.959
on the things that go wrong
here in Littleton, do we?

22:16.043 --> 22:19.546
No, that's not my town. No, sir.

22:19.629 --> 22:22.632
We move forward.

22:24.009 --> 22:26.636
We make things better.

22:27.971 --> 22:29.264
It's gonna take more

22:29.347 --> 22:32.434
than some-some puny space rock

22:32.517 --> 22:35.437
to crush the spirit

22:35.520 --> 22:38.523
of <i> El Ayudante!</i>

22:43.111 --> 22:44.988
The Helper.

22:45.906 --> 22:47.074
-(whooping)
-CONLEY: Yeah,

22:47.157 --> 22:49.284
he's too damn tough for that.

22:49.367 --> 22:51.578
Gloria, will you please join me
by my side here?

22:51.661 --> 22:53.080
Just, uh, cozy up
right next to me.

22:53.163 --> 22:54.664
Hey, there we go.

22:54.748 --> 22:56.792
All right.
(laughs)

22:56.875 --> 22:59.419
♪ ♪

23:25.695 --> 23:27.697
♪ ♪

23:33.745 --> 23:35.705
Strange.

23:54.891 --> 23:57.227
♪ ♪

24:03.024 --> 24:04.693
(whimpering)

24:04.776 --> 24:07.445
(screaming)

24:17.873 --> 24:20.417
(whimpering)

24:39.561 --> 24:42.439
Well, listen, you know,
I'm-I'm a practical man.

24:42.522 --> 24:44.149
Mm-hmm.

24:44.232 --> 24:46.818
-I don't scare easily.
-Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

24:46.902 --> 24:48.570
I don't get paranoid,
it's just...

24:48.653 --> 24:52.199
it feels like there's someone
trying to play a trick on me.

24:52.282 --> 24:54.576
-Okay.
-Oh, this is gonna sound crazy.

24:54.659 --> 24:56.411
Okay, okay, stop.

24:56.494 --> 24:57.913
What happened?

24:57.996 --> 24:59.414
I'm not afraid of crazy.

24:59.497 --> 25:01.416
CONLEY: It's as if my faith
is being tested.

25:01.500 --> 25:03.585
First with the car and then...

25:05.837 --> 25:07.380
...that spider.

25:10.884 --> 25:12.719
Hey.

25:12.802 --> 25:14.429
-Hey!
-ANA: What are you doing?

25:14.512 --> 25:17.557
You saw this last night,
didn't you?

25:18.642 --> 25:20.268
-Why, you little smart-ass!
-Hey!

25:20.352 --> 25:22.062
Get your hands off my son.

25:23.855 --> 25:26.066
(speaks Spanish)

25:28.026 --> 25:29.736
Look, if you have
a problem with him,

25:29.819 --> 25:32.697
you'll address it with me.
Do you understand?

25:34.032 --> 25:37.035
-NICKI: You okay?
-ANA: I'm fine. Thank you.

25:38.036 --> 25:39.454
(knocking)

25:39.537 --> 25:41.414
<i>JASON:</i>
<i>Coming.</i>

25:45.043 --> 25:46.253
Hey.

25:46.336 --> 25:47.629
What's up? How are you?

25:47.712 --> 25:49.422
I'm just checking in on you.

25:49.506 --> 25:51.967
You've seemed
a little off lately.

25:52.050 --> 25:53.426
Oh, right, um...

25:53.510 --> 25:55.387
yeah, I just had a lot
on my mind.

25:55.470 --> 25:56.596
Yeah.

25:56.680 --> 25:59.140
Well, don't forget
the bright side.

25:59.224 --> 26:01.309
You know, you've been hoping
for this town to turn itself

26:01.393 --> 26:03.478
around for a little while,
and now we have some reason

26:03.561 --> 26:05.438
-to-to hope, it seems.
-Right.

26:05.522 --> 26:06.982
Oh, because of The Helper?

26:07.065 --> 26:08.650
Yeah, I suppose.

26:08.733 --> 26:10.318
It's obviously not Conley.

26:10.402 --> 26:11.945
I know you know that, right?

26:12.028 --> 26:14.030
I mean, he's way too...
selfish and greedy

26:14.114 --> 26:16.157
to help anyone besides himself.

26:16.241 --> 26:20.036
None of us is
beyond redemption, Jason.

26:20.120 --> 26:21.663
People can change.

26:21.746 --> 26:25.458
You know, even
the most stubborn of us.

26:25.542 --> 26:27.127
All right.

26:27.210 --> 26:29.379
Well, don't get caught up
on the who.

26:29.462 --> 26:32.507
It's not about the who.

26:32.590 --> 26:34.175
Good night.

26:35.135 --> 26:37.178
Good night.

26:41.266 --> 26:43.101
JASON:
Okay, maybe she's right.

26:43.184 --> 26:46.354
I can't make Littleton better
by destroying it.

26:46.438 --> 26:47.856
A few more lights on that sign,

26:47.939 --> 26:50.233
and we'll really put
Littleton on the map.

26:59.492 --> 27:01.745
(electrical buzzing)

27:17.302 --> 27:19.554
(popping, crackling)

27:36.321 --> 27:37.781
I have apnea.

27:37.864 --> 27:41.076
This power outage
could kill me if I can't plug in

27:41.159 --> 27:41.910
my machine.

27:41.993 --> 27:43.203
WOMAN:
That's right.

27:43.286 --> 27:44.621
I can't operate my pumps!

27:44.704 --> 27:46.790
My-my register doesn't work!

27:46.873 --> 27:49.626
Nothing! When's the power
coming back on?

27:49.709 --> 27:51.711
(clamoring,
overlapping shouting)

27:51.795 --> 27:53.963
All right.
Now, everyone, please, uh,

27:54.047 --> 27:56.466
settle down, you know, uh,
settle down.

27:56.549 --> 27:58.259
Well, I just got off the phone
with the governor's office,

27:58.343 --> 28:00.887
and it seems we have a bigger
problem than we first thought.

28:00.970 --> 28:03.306
-Uh... sorry.
-WOMAN: What does that mean?

28:04.724 --> 28:06.434
Bear with me here.

28:06.518 --> 28:08.770
For some unknown reason...

28:08.853 --> 28:10.855
the new sign caused
some kind of power overload

28:10.939 --> 28:13.358
that destroyed the
Littleton County power center.

28:13.441 --> 28:14.609
-MAN: What?
-It says...

28:14.692 --> 28:17.237
"destroyed."

28:17.320 --> 28:18.780
Well, uh, (clears throat)
obviously,

28:18.863 --> 28:20.949
this is a-a serious
infrastructure problem,

28:21.032 --> 28:23.743
and, uh, it's gonna take
some time to rebuild.

28:23.827 --> 28:26.287
-Well, how long?
-Well, it could be weeks.

28:26.371 --> 28:27.372
-Weeks?
-(all clamoring)

28:27.455 --> 28:28.415
That's too long!

28:28.498 --> 28:29.958
(overlapping shouting)

28:30.041 --> 28:31.626
MRS. TURNER:
Why don't you just...

28:31.709 --> 28:34.295
you know, do your <i> thing?</i>

28:34.379 --> 28:36.172
Yeah, fix this.

28:36.256 --> 28:37.632
You're The Helper.

28:37.715 --> 28:40.802
Oh, well, I-I never
technically said that.

28:40.885 --> 28:42.470
-(all muttering)
-ANA: So...

28:42.554 --> 28:44.347
Wait, so you didn't add
those lights?

28:44.431 --> 28:45.640
The ones that caused the surge!

28:45.723 --> 28:47.892
We don't, uh,
exactly know what happened.

28:47.976 --> 28:49.644
Hey! You bungled this!

28:49.727 --> 28:51.020
-Just admit it!
-Yeah!

28:51.104 --> 28:52.480
(all clamoring)

28:52.564 --> 28:53.815
And we can't wait weeks!

28:53.898 --> 28:56.651
I'll bet he's trying
to force us to leave,

28:56.734 --> 28:59.821
so that he can buy us all out
on a discount!

28:59.904 --> 29:01.156
I bet that's exactly
what's going on!

29:01.239 --> 29:03.575
(all clamoring)

29:05.743 --> 29:09.914
(overlapping shouting,
clamoring)

29:13.376 --> 29:15.003
Gloria!

29:15.086 --> 29:16.838
(clamoring continues)

29:16.921 --> 29:18.006
(exclaims)

29:18.089 --> 29:19.007
Whoa...

29:19.090 --> 29:20.508
It's him!

29:20.592 --> 29:23.636
-Wait! Hold on! Wait!
-Grab him!

29:23.720 --> 29:25.180
Goddamn it, that kid!

29:25.263 --> 29:26.764
-What are you drawing?
-Don't let him get away!

29:26.848 --> 29:27.724
Ha!

29:27.807 --> 29:29.559
{\an5}-You see?
Look! Look! Look! Look!
-Hey!

29:29.642 --> 29:30.894
-MAN: What?
-You see?

29:30.977 --> 29:32.687
It's all the things
that have been happening

29:32.770 --> 29:33.855
in our town, look!

29:33.938 --> 29:36.191
I don't know
what sort of witchcraft

29:36.274 --> 29:38.026
or conspiracy is at play here,

29:38.109 --> 29:40.695
but whatever it is,

29:40.778 --> 29:42.530
this little brat
had something to do with it!

29:42.614 --> 29:45.325
MAN: You caused this mess,
Mayor. Do something!

29:45.408 --> 29:46.659
CONLEY:
Yeah, look!

29:46.743 --> 29:48.745
He draws it and then it happens!

29:48.828 --> 29:49.996
-MAN: Come on!
-Look!

29:50.079 --> 29:52.540
No, my son has nothing to do
with this.

29:52.624 --> 29:54.375
You know what,
you have been harassing him

29:54.459 --> 29:56.211
since all of these
changes started!

29:56.294 --> 29:57.462
BEAU:
He's blaming a kid!

29:57.545 --> 29:59.881
No! No, no, no!

29:59.964 --> 30:02.175
ANA: This is your mess--
now, you fix it!

30:02.258 --> 30:04.177
-(clamoring)
-No!

30:04.260 --> 30:07.055
(indistinct shouting)

30:13.978 --> 30:15.355
Hey! Hey! Hey!

30:15.438 --> 30:16.564
Stop!

30:16.648 --> 30:18.233
It was me!

30:18.316 --> 30:20.777
Okay?

30:20.860 --> 30:22.904
WOMAN:
What? No.

30:22.987 --> 30:25.240
JASON: I'm sorry everything's
gotten so out of hand.

30:25.323 --> 30:26.366
(all murmuring)

30:26.449 --> 30:28.284
You did this?

30:28.368 --> 30:31.579
The... the-the spider.

30:31.663 --> 30:33.414
The paint job.

30:33.498 --> 30:35.708
Yes.

30:36.876 --> 30:39.754
'Cause you weren't helping
the town, you were hurting it.

30:39.837 --> 30:42.090
I was just trying
to make things better.

30:44.175 --> 30:46.427
It was supposed to help.

30:46.511 --> 30:48.179
Okay?

30:49.973 --> 30:52.559
Things don't always go
like we plan.

30:53.351 --> 30:55.061
CONLEY:
Show us.

30:55.144 --> 30:56.563
MAN:
Yeah.

30:56.646 --> 30:58.106
WOMAN:
How did he do it?

30:58.189 --> 30:59.524
Um...

31:00.400 --> 31:02.527
Anybody got some matches?

31:04.487 --> 31:06.281
Here we go.

31:11.327 --> 31:13.204
(all gasping, exclaiming)

31:16.541 --> 31:20.253
Sorry, baby, I let you down.

31:21.504 --> 31:24.173
(grunts, pants)

31:24.257 --> 31:26.968
What the hell is that?

31:30.888 --> 31:33.266
So this is how
you've been doing it?

31:35.351 --> 31:37.812
I'm gonna fix the lights.
I just need a little time.

31:37.895 --> 31:41.316
"Fix the lights"?

31:41.399 --> 31:44.485
We can change the entire town.

31:44.569 --> 31:47.280
It'll be like a...

31:47.363 --> 31:48.323
a new Vegas.

31:48.406 --> 31:49.782
-Vegas?
-Yeah.

31:49.866 --> 31:52.201
(Conley laughing)

31:53.911 --> 31:55.330
How do you work this thing?

31:55.413 --> 31:57.081
I'm not gonna let you do that.

32:01.419 --> 32:02.920
"Let me"?

32:04.589 --> 32:06.758
Take it.

32:08.092 --> 32:11.262
Hey! Stop!
Get away from the model!

32:14.307 --> 32:16.601
(rumbling)

32:35.578 --> 32:37.789
♪ ♪

32:56.599 --> 32:58.726
JASON: Thank the Lord,
no serious injuries.

32:58.810 --> 33:01.604
But the property damage...

33:01.688 --> 33:03.064
Do you think we can fix it?

33:03.147 --> 33:05.024
The model? Nah.

33:05.108 --> 33:07.402
No, I don't think so.

33:07.485 --> 33:10.238
Feel like it wouldn't work
anymore anyway.

33:10.321 --> 33:12.573
I wasn't talking about no model.

33:12.657 --> 33:16.244
When people come together,
broken things can be mended.

33:16.327 --> 33:18.579
{\an8}Yeah, but how are we gonna pay
for all this?

33:18.663 --> 33:22.208
{\an8}JASON: I feel like we might have
all the resources we need.

33:22.291 --> 33:25.420
{\an5}NEWSWOMAN:
We've been able to confirm this
is one of the largest pieces

33:25.503 --> 33:29.298
of unbroken gold ever reported,
which obviously has

33:29.382 --> 33:32.135
major implications
for Littleton's fortunes...

33:32.218 --> 33:34.762
{\an5}<i>NARRATOR:</i>
<i>We can never calculate</i>
<i>what change our actions</i>

33:34.846 --> 33:36.639
<i>will bring into the world,</i>

33:36.723 --> 33:38.224
<i>despite our best intentions,</i>

33:38.307 --> 33:40.977
<i>and whether they will be</i>
<i>for good or ill.</i>

33:41.060 --> 33:44.772
<i>Yet without action,</i>
<i>the stars themselves go cold.</i>

33:44.856 --> 33:47.567
<i>Jason Grant wanted to change</i>
<i>the world for the better,</i>

33:47.650 --> 33:50.111
<i>but the power to do so</i>
<i>got the best of him</i>

33:50.194 --> 33:52.447
<i>until he lost it all.</i>
<i>But today,</i>

33:52.530 --> 33:55.283
<i>perhaps losing it all-- both</i>
<i>for Mr. Grant and for the town</i>

33:55.366 --> 33:57.452
<i>of Littleton-- was</i>
<i>the beginning of something new.</i>

33:57.535 --> 34:01.080
<i>Lonely hands find each other</i>
<i>in the shadows,</i>

34:01.164 --> 34:04.333
<i>both in our imperfect world</i>
<i>and in...</i>

34:04.417 --> 34:05.460
<i>the Twilight Zone.</i>

